    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a lineup heavily indexed on high-floor consistency and specific category-chasing, most notably in the SB department. **Yordan Alvarez** remains our premier option with a 74.41 score; despite a respectable xERA of 4.19 from his opponent, **Yordan Alvarez**\u2019s elite xwOBA and favorable #2 spot in the order make him an essential anchor. He is closely followed by **Trea Turner**, who earns a 70.46 score today. Even against a standard matchup, **Trea Turner** provides massive utility as our primary stolen base engine; his aggressive base-running remains a non-negotiable component of our offensive strategy, despite the minor efficiency friction caused by an opposing pitcher with a high pick-off threat. **Kyle Schwarber** also warrants a \"Strong\" designation (69.69), as his elite xwOBA provides significant insulation against the standard variances of a 5x5 Roto environment.\n\nThe bottom half of the lineup highlights our commitment to efficiency over raw counting stats, as seen in the decision to bench **Dillon Dingler**. While **Dillon Dingler** flirted with relevance (36.10), he ultimately fell below our 40.0 floor due to a combination of a stagnant platoon outlook and the lack of a premium lineup spot, leading us to favor the multi-category upside of **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (60.49). Although **Pete Crow-Armstrong** faces a stiff test against a high-end catcher, his dynamic platoon splits and speed profile outweigh the risk. Similarly, **Hyeseong Kim** (60.67) is a surprise riser; despite a theoretical platoon disadvantage, his park factors and projected lineup efficiency justify a start. We remain cautious regarding **Victor Scott II**, whose 43.78 score teeters on the edge of our rotation requirements. While his speed is elite, the low-leverage #9 lineup slot significantly hampers his run-scoring potential. \n\nFinally, managers should monitor the \"Lineup Pending\" status for **Hyeseong Kim**, **Trea Turner**, **Kyle Schwarber**, **Kazuma Okamoto**, **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, and **Luke Raley**, as our scores rely on these projected defensive placements. **Luke Raley** (45.67) represents a niche play\u2014his score is bolstered by a favorable outlook against a pitcher with a notoriously slow delivery, which we project will facilitate his efficiency on the base paths. Meanwhile, we continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, who remains sidelined on the IL. We are currently holding **Carson Benge**, **Gary Sanchez**, **Zac Veen**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, **Josh Smith**, **Chase Meidroth**, and **Luis Pena** in reserve, but none present a compelling enough case to displace our current starting nine given the optimized platoon and speed advantages currently in play.",
